text: To be honest, The 1st Annabelle wasn't that great.   The doll hardly moved (besides rocking in a chair and floating in one scene) , and the movie is just full of shoots of the doll sitting on a shelf or in a chair, and the camera zooming in on it. The movie (plot wise) was essentially "Oh shit the doll is back, whatever will we do?" and the wife, with the skeptical husband, trying to protect her child from getting rekt by a creepy ass doll.   Oh, and don't even me started on the jumpscares. Just because your movie is full of scenes of doll close ups, and filler doesn't mean that jumpscares will make the movie scary or atleast, any less terrible.  I don't have high hopes for this Annabelle either. I'm assuming that there, of course, will be more doll close up, and more jumpscares to distract you from the lack of plot. However, hopefully they'll be a bit more action since now, we're getting the actually ghost of a dead girl rather than her hideous doll counterpart.

Afterward, you'll hear them walking out of the theater saying things like "That wasn't scary" or, "That sucked"  Deep down, they were frightened the whole time.  You can tell the adults who do it. text: The thing about the Annabelle movies is that they're not based on true stories, The Conjuring movies however are. No one knows how the Annabelle doll came to be evil, the only thing we know is that it was actually a Raggedy Ann doll and it infested these two girls lives in the '60's after one of them had bought it at a retail shop. Once Annabelle started haunting them they called Ed and Lorraine Warren and they locked it up in their house along with other haunted items that they investigated. But no one truly knows what exactly happened to the doll or why a demon has manifested itself onto the doll, these movies are just ideas and made up stories about what could have happened to the doll. Regardless, the first one was very entertaining and I'm excited for the next one!

text: EL JB Jumpscares will always be apart of horror movies, im not really understanding what all the bitching about them is about. I think you're looking at jumpscares the wrong way. They're not supposed to be scary, they're supposed to catch you off guard and keep you on the edge. That's literally it. Think of a horror movie like a roller coaster. Would you prefer a coaster that just goes straight in a line like a subway or one that goes up and down and upside down. Take 0:58 for example. The scene starts out with a jump scare, but then the scary part comes AFTER when Annabel starts attacking the girl. Jumpscares are presents. They're the gift wrapping, the real scary part comes afterward when you open the gift. If that makes sense... :)

text: Unoriginal piece of garbage. The movie does not develop its characters, the characters make the stupidest decisions and the jump scares are back to back (for about an hour and 30 min). Jump scares are predictable and clearly "inspired"/stolen from other movies (for example the vomit possession from Evil Dead). Couldn't finish the movie in the end as there was no compelling story (got to about 1,5 hours) or character development. Good way to check if there is any character development is asking your self mid-movie: Would i care if all the characters died right now? If the answer is no, quit watching.   What saddens me is that this movie is making so much money in box office, which in turn will result in more of this regurgitated garbage getting released. Shimmer of hope this year are movies like "Get out": good acting, great story and clever scares. If you don't care for story or character development but enjoy countless unoriginal back-to-back jump scares definitely go see this movie.

text: I think it was dumb for Janice to be Annabelle. That makes no sense to me, if she was adopted, her legal name would still be Janice so it makes no sense that her name to suddenly become "Annabelle"-  that was a lousy attempt at trying to be clever and connect Annabelle to the Conjuring. A prequel was a dumb idea in the first place, I think a sequel to the opening of the Conjuring would've been far superior! I guess that's what they're gonna do in Annabelle: The Sequel (Pt. 3). Maybe they did this to end on a cliff hanger and set up for a pt. 3. But ala, this movie was very confusing, from the beginning I was thinking "now why would the director have the name of the foster family's daughter be Annabelle? Is he ignoring the beginning of the Conjuring?". It was entertaining, just confusing. 5/10 and overrated. I feel like the reason this movie and IT are doing strong at the box office, is not because these were good movies, but because audiences are attempting to send a message to Hollywood that they want R-rated horror. I value gore and R rating too, but the output hasn't been well seeing as both IT and Annabelle are extremely overrated. Next will be an overrated Conjuring 3. Oh, and I don't see how Annabelle or IT got a f***** R-rating in the first as there was little gore but more of a focus on jump scares. I guess rated R for run for cover from the jump scares. /rant. :-)

text: One of the best horror movies ever made! Just an absolute masterpiece from start to finish. It's not your typical jump scare horror and it's not predictable. The way they use long silence instead of jump scares has made this the first movie to ever make me afraid. It's bone-chilling. More horror producers should use this tactic of silence because it's so much more effective than loud banging music every 10 minutes when a face appears. That moment when the girl is in the wheelchair in the barn and she says, "I'm fine. Everything's fine." Oh my god, that shook me up for hours. Watch it! 10/10
